However, a simple rule is that if we have a bug for something, we should include a test with the fix unless there is a good reason not to (test is brittle, takes too long, too complex, etc.). I think this is a fair rule and it doesn\'t overburden contributors.\\n", "@ijuma Sure, I certainly agree that it is a good principle and common to \\"add test for a bug\\". Because the fact that there is a bug indicates this is probably hard to detect. But I feel that, if we couldn\'t require developers who originally write these code to add test for `finally`, it probably indicates that the benefits of these tests are not worth the developer\'s time; if this is not worth developer\'s time who write the feature, then we shouldn\'t require contributors who fix the bug to write the test. It would be a fair rule to hold developers of the feature to no lower standard than those who help fix their code, right?\\n\\nIt would be good to take cost of time into account and be consistent about a standard for test since there will be growing number of these bug fixes moving forward. The argument I make here is for long term development rather than trying to avoid adding test for a specific bug :)\\n", "@zhuchen1018 I think we\'re going in circles a bit. I\'ll leave some thoughts and if you want to discuss the topic more generally, then please start a mailing list thread. So here it goes:\\n- I think focusing on a language construct (`finally`) is perhaps the wrong way to think about it. Let\'s describe the issue', metadata={'source': 'data/kafka/repository_data.txt'}), Document(page_content=" all of those issues have been addressed and a release candidate has been generated (which is currently the case for 3.3.2), then unless a blocker issue (which is either a serious recently-unearthed issue, or a newly-introduced regression) is raised, the release will proceed without generating a new candidate.\\r\\n\\r\\nIn this particular case, the bug here doesn't appear to be a regression, and IMO it's not serious enough to qualify as a blocker for the 3.3.2 or 3.4.0 releases. What can probably happen here is that the fix gets backported to the 3.3 and 3.4 branches, but only after the in-flight 3.3.2 and 3.4.0 releases are pushed out. Then, the fix will be present in versions 3.3.3 (if one is released) and 3.4.1.\\r\\n\\r\\nIf that's unsatisfactory, you can reach out on the 3.3.2 and 3.4.0 discussion threads on the dev mailing list and make a case to treat this issue as a blocker by including details on the impact it's having on you/your environment, whether it's a regression (and if not, how old it is), and how much risk it presents.\\r\\n\\r\\nFull disclosure: I'm the release manager for 3.3.2 and wouldn't mind seeing this added to 3.3.2 (even at the cost of generating a new release candidate), but only if we can also get it included in 3.4.0, to prevent problems from arising should users choose to upgrade from", metadata={'source': 'data/kafka/repository_data.txt'}), Document(page_content='\'s more useful for developers.", "Also, it\'s not possible to enable both html and XML at the same time (and that\'s the reason for the current setup).", "About the report level, medium is the default so we are making it report less here?", "Yeah, I think they would be failing currently because we have toggled the `ignoreFailures` setting appropriately. I filed the JIRA as part of follow up on code quality before I saw that Colin had enabled some findbugs stuff earlier -- I can update PR/commit title. However, the setting for xml reports is still probably worth toggling -- currently you can\'t get at the info easily from Jenkins, e.g. see lack of reported info on a recent Jenkins build: https://builds.apache.org/job/kafka-trunk-jdk8/2312/. I know the report type can only be one type (which seems silly, but is an upstream constraint), but I think the switch to xml by default is the right move. I highly doubt devs are looking at the html reports in any normal circumstances and at least the xml reports get incorporated into Jenkins, allow us to visualize history, etc.\\r\\n\\r\\nRegarding report level, I think being explicit is good. I mainly set high because that\'s a level that consistently reports real bugs and its the level that goes red when reported in Jenkins, but I\'m happy to reduce it if we want to address everything at medium or higher level.", "@ewencp the report is empty because there are no warnings in the code right?
